Comment: THIS REVIEW CONTAINS SPOILERS. Please skip if you havenâ€™t seen the film yet. I am thoroughly impressed by Mother! Where to even begin? I was not expecting the movie to unfold the way it did. It was truly a shift from heaven to hell... and although it grew more rapidly hellish towards the end, it was subtly intertwined throughout. The movie felt like a nightmare visualized. After finishing it, I knew that there was cryptic messages riddled throughout. Initially, I assumed the story was about a womanâ€™s journey with a narcissistic mate, but after reading some reviews, I can TOTALLY see how it would be the Bible story re-imagined in a peculiar, creative, and out of the box way. BRAVO for Jen Laws acting and the directors vision. The film was both beautiful and disturbing beyond belief. Itâ€™s a work of art, which like most abstract pieces, are quickly dismissed by simple minded folks. The storytelling in this film was MASTERFUL. One that Iâ€™m sure will be considered a gem in the future, but in present times will be overlooked, just like many great works of art.

Comment:
This movie is a MASTERPIECE, and whoever doesnâ€™t think so does not understand cinema or did not understand the MOVIE. And I will try to explain why* (SPOILERS AHEAD!!!):
*(This is what I got from the movie. I am sure other people felt differently, which is normal)


This movie is a tale. Not for children but for grown-ups. It is the adult version of, for instance, "hansel & gretel", etc. And not only because of the plot itself but also for the way Aronofsky presents it (the beginning is the end, cyclic-wise). Therefore nothing that happens in the movie is strictly real but it is a metaphor of the human condition. This movie is A TALE of the human condition. 
Jealousy, Narcissism, unconditional love, lust, avarice, pride. All the most beautiful/dangerous human feelings are taken to unrealistic extremes, but the movie shows you how amazing/cruel our life sometimes is, because we FEEL these emotions in our daily life. He (Javier Bardem) is a narcissistic motherfucker that would do ANYTHING for his ego and to feel loved by others. He is a sink of energy. Dont tell me you have not found people like this in your life. Whereas she (Jennifer Lawrence) unconditionally loves him. Even after he got the baby killed because of his EGO, she is still willing to give him her heart. "is this enough for you?" she asks, and IT IS NOT! It will never be enough.
The couple (M.Pfeifer and Ed Harris) and their children are the highest exponents of selfishness. They bring their shit to the house and Mother (Jen. Lawrence) feels it and is really disgusted by this. And M. Pfeifer is JEALOUS of her, because deep inside knows that Mother is a good, loving and charming person. That is why M. Pfeifer is proud and happy of fucking up her life, and you feel it with the way they look at each other and the faces they put.
And the final mess, caused uniquely by HIS EGO (JAVIER BARDEM), where the house is practically a Civil War settlement, is used only to show how even in the most adverse circumstances Mother still has energy to create and to try to find a solution for her family.

mother!Â is an allegory about God and the Earth.Â Javier Bardemâ€™s character, whom Iâ€™ll refer to as The Poet, is God, andÂ Jennifer Lawrenceâ€™s character, whom Iâ€™ll refer to as The Mother, is Mother Earth with the house standing in for the environment. From there, the story attempts to be a biblical allegory of both the Old and New Testament as well as a brief, deeply misanthropic view of human history.

Ed Harrisâ€™ man represents Adam. When heâ€™s puking in the bathroom, we quickly see an injury right where his rib would be. In the next scene, his wife (Michelle Pfeiffer), representing Eve shows up. Theyâ€™re allowed to wander the house, but are told specifically not to go the poetâ€™s office, but they do so anyway where Eve accidentally breaks the fire crystal. Theyâ€™re then exiled and soon begin having sex elsewhere in the house, thus representing original sin and manâ€™s fall from grace after eating the forbidden fruit from the tree of knowledge in the Garden of Eden.

ï¿¼ï¿¼

Image via Paramount

Then the coupleâ€™s sons (BrianÂ and Domhnall Gleeson) come along arguing about their dying fatherâ€™s will. In their argument, one brother kills the other (Cain and Abel). The parents and the poet carry the dead brother out of the house and the surviving brother runs away. The poet and the parents then return later that night for a wake, and more and more guests come to grieve, but the wake then becomes a chaotic party where, after numerous protestations to not sit on an un-braced sink, the sink becomes unmoored from the wall and water pours into the house. Thus we have humanityâ€™s downfall following the slaying of Abel and eventually the flood.

ï¿¼ï¿¼

Image via Paramount

After the water pours into the house and the guests leave, the mother admonishes the poet, saying that he wonâ€™t even have sex with her. They then proceed to have sex, and the following morning, she announces sheâ€™s pregnant. Heâ€™s then struck with a flash of inspiration and goes downstairs naked to write. When he shows her the finished product, she sees a vision of the world rejuvenated and says that itâ€™s beautiful. However, once again people start flooding into their home and although sheâ€™s prepared a nice, quiet meal for her and the poet, the fully pregnant mother is overwhelmed by a throng of people.

At this point, the story is kind of leaving the biblical text behind and moving more into historical record. The New Testament element is that the Motherâ€™s child is a Christ figure, but before heâ€™s born, the Mother goes through a hellish experience surrounded by war, human trafficking, and other nightmarish visuals before the Poet finally reappears and brings her to his private office where she can give birth to their son. The allegory here seems to be that God abandoned the Earth for stretches at a time before the messiah figure was born.

ï¿¼

Image via Paramount

But then mankind screws it all up again and snatches away the baby, kills it, and eats its flesh as they worship at an altar to the Poet. They then assault the Mother, ripping at her clothes and beating her senseless before sheâ€™s finally able to escape, go down to the basement, smash open an oil drum, and set the entire place on fire. So even when presented with a savior and total innocent, mankind only kills, eats the flesh of the Messiah (i.e. communion), then proceeds to assault Mother Earth with God absent yet again, and Mother Earth finally uses oil (i.e. fossil fuels) to destroy herself along with humanity with God powerless to stop it.

ï¿¼

Image via Paramount

The Poet then takes the motherâ€™s charred body and takes out her beating heart with his hands. She turns to ash and the burned heart becomes a new fire crystal. He places the new fire crystal in its holder and weâ€™re brought back to the beginning of the film where placing the fire crystal in the holder undoes the fire damage and a woman wakes up in their bed. The only thing thatâ€™s different this time is a different young woman wakes up in the bed. So basically the Earth and humanity will die and at best God will simply do everything all over again because he needs to create and desires love from his creations.

Additionally, throughout the film, the Mother will pause when getting overwhelmed, and touch the walls of the house where sheâ€™ll have a vision of a heart thatâ€™s slowing dying. Furthermore, the house continues to bleed, crack, and fall apart. This reinforcing the notion that Mother Nature is seeing that the environment is dying, especially as more people enter the house and cause chaos.

ï¿¼

Image via Paramount

None of this is surprising when you consider that Aronofsky is an atheist, heâ€™s staunchly environmental, and that humanityâ€™s downfall in the face of an environmental catastrophe and an absent God was the theme of the directorâ€™s previous film,Â Noah.

To be fair, not everything in the film is a one-to-one ratio, and not everything, especially in the second half, lines up with the biblical text or the entire course of human history. Does Ed Harrisâ€™ character being a doctor mean anything? Perhaps, but Iâ€™m not sure what. Why does all the war and chaos precede the birth of the messiah figure rather than follow it? Isnâ€™t there war and chaos on both sides of the New Testament? Additionally, the God represented here isnâ€™t the only view of a supreme being, but for Aronofsky, itâ€™s how he views Godâ€”as a figure who is frequently absent when needed yet constantly feels the need both to create and to be loved despite the terrible behavior of mankind and the abuse they shower upon Mother Earth.

ï¿¼

Image via Paramount

There are also loose ends that I canâ€™t tie up or figure out if they even represent anything. Iâ€™m not sure what the yellow liquid the Mother keeps drinking represents. I donâ€™t know why 911 answers the phone when the Mother calls (who does Mother Earth call in the event of an emergency?). But despite these lingering questions, Iâ€™m fairly confident in my reading that the movie is about the relationship between God, Mother Earth, the environment, and humanity with Aronofsky coming down on the side of humanity being a plague upon the Earth.

ï¿¼

Image via Paramount

Iâ€™ve also heard a few other readings of the film, but I donâ€™t think they account for the entire picture. One reading seesÂ mother!Â as a story about creation, looking at the Poet as a stand in for all artists and the double-edged sword about the need to create and the destruction that a work can wreak when itâ€™s released to the public. While I think Aronofsky certainly feels some kinship to his God figure in terms of an artist needing to create, this reading fails to account for the copious amounts of biblical symbolism, and, more importantly, fails to account for the Mother.

ï¿¼

Image via Paramount

Another reading of the film sees this as a semi-autobiographical take for both Aronofsky and Lawrence. First, Pfeifferâ€™s character makes the comment that the Poet is a little old for the Mother. Aronofsky is 48, and Lawrence is 27. Thereâ€™s also the aforementioned kinship between Aronofsky and the God figure, and the frustration of being worshipped by fans but also the fear they create with their constant devotion. Then, when the Mother is attacked and her clothes are being ripped from her body, you can point to how when Lawrenceâ€™s nude photos of were hacked from her phone and leaked online, she later toldÂ Vanity FairÂ that the hack was a â€œsex crime.â€ But again, this reading fails to account for the entirety of the movie and the overarching allegory.

Thatâ€™s not to say my reading ofÂ mother!Â is the only valid assessment of the film or that art can only have one interpretation. However, I do believe that my case has the most evidence to support it, and if you disagree, I have one more thing to add:

Look at the title.

Image via Paramount Pictures

Comment: The religious symbolism aside I think this film is also satirising our obsessed culture with celebrities, how crazy fans hunt down celebs, bombard them and are obsessed with their personal lives and children and how this behaviour effects the celebrity's family while the celebrity himself loves the attention, blissfully unaware of the mental damage it has done to his family, I seen the baby death scene as the father turning the child into a celebrity but ultimately ruining the kids life leading to his suicide and with the media 'eating up the news' and crying about his death like we do with celebrities in real life when in reality we never known them, imagine how weird you would feel if hundreds of complete strangers were crying and saying they'll miss them about a family member of your own? I thought the burning of the house meant she couldn't accept the reality and made up this world inside of her mind to cope with her reality but the course of the film slowly brings back all those horrific memories into the fantasy/coma world she has created for herself. And in the end she forgets again, only to awake to the same fantasy, kind of like what happens to leo in shutter Island, I thought it was all in Jennifer's head.

Title: mother! movie (2017) - official trailer - paramount pictures
Comment:
I really dislike trailers that hide or misdirect the actual tone of the movie. Here, I was anticipating a creepy thriller/horror, under the impression that Lawrence's character was a unstable introverted woman who did not want anyone in her family's house (or something to that effect). Other than re watching the trailer and noticing one or two vague instances of possible hints, I wasn't expecting a movie that was 100% allegorical to the stories of the Christian religion, and I feel like the amount of religious themes that the trailer chose to omit seemed like a intentional misdirection to get more than just the religious folk in there. Not everyone might agree with that, but that is what I took away after watching the movie and considering the themes. It felt like a cheap tactic to get a bigger audience turnout and I can't really respect that. At least if it was more upfront in the trailer I'd have known this wouldn't have been the movie for me (and if that was supposed to be the big twist or something, it was not well done in that regard)

Besides this, I understood the symbolism and allegories just fine, but the tone of the movie just felt... Bitter, I guess? There was a lot of gross and abhorrent imagery and scenes that made it surpass being disturbing in a way to have the audience reflect on a message, and instead seemed to exist to purposefully make people disgusted. It seemed like it was trying to shock just to shock, as rather than consider a deeper meaning, i just felt upset and uncomfortable having watched it (and that's coming from someone who doesn't get disturbed by much). I also found the sound design to be sub par, as it seemed kind of odd and jarring at times, but that's a small nitpick. 

The acting was indeed well executed, and the beginning of the film did have me initially intrigued, but other than that it didn't have much to offer, to me at least. I suppose the real problems imo are the over-the-top gross visual imagery near the end and the chrisitan symbolism that drives 100% of the movie's logic and story, which i understand isn't a problem for everyone, but as it is not something i find that interesting or i believe in, i just simply could not enjoy it.

Comment: I know this movie has been divisive, and maybe Iâ€™m a little late to the mother! discussions that that we are in may of 2018, but watching this as a surrealist interpretation drama is more of an experience than with knowledge of explanations, religious or not.  Now, I will say that  I knew from the get go that Darren Aronofsky set out to make a planet earth and Mother Nature message intertwined with religious (possibly sac religious depending on who you talk to) metaphors.  But as someone who watched this in a Kubrick like fashion, where the answer is not as important as the interpretation that speaks to you, it gave me a new perspective on the film that I really appreciate and perhaps will not forget for a long time.  And I think if a movie achieves this, then in my mind the film and itâ€™s artist have succeeded , even if that means no standing ovations from general audiences...film has always been used to break barriers in how we approach life, and I think that philosophy is dying in a world populated with much Hollywood cash-grabs which is why I feel this fascination, entertainment value, and appreciation for mother!

This was the most disgusting and disturbing movie I have ever seen and I consider that director needs some psychiatric help, because this is definitelly not a product of a sane mind. According to trailer, I thought itÂ´s going to be some good horror about a haunted house but it was not even scary in a real goosebumps meaning. It was just abominable.  My philosophical self realized there are some biblical themes without even reading about it, but I would say it was more like satanistic way to depict religion. "God" was represented by a maniacal selfish sociopath who was abusing his wife all the time and didnt give a sh*t about her feelings, needs or didnt even have basic decency to ask his wife if she is ok with inviting large group of people to their house.
And when the crowd massacred the baby, I was so disgusted and shaken, I wanted to throw up. The picture of gutted newborn was such a psycho, I dont believe any sane human cand create it. I regret the time I spent on this movie, it was like poison for normality. I dont understand how such a sickening madness can be praised, just because it pretends to be art. 
I am going to watch classical regency romance for a whole month, just to retrieve my good taste. :-D

Title: mother! movie (2017) - official trailer - paramount pictures
Comment:
I really enjoyed this. It was (as per usual with Aronofsky) a bit hamfisted but I don't think I've ever watched a movie really capture the essence of what a dream is like quite like this one did. The way it just barrels on and never lingers on time compressions and obviously bizarre situations. Yeah, it's not **about** a dream as such - but it played out like one. 

It's pretty obvious what it's about really. Some of the clues didn't hit home at once (like the wound on Ed Harris back when he's barfing - it wasn't until I was thinking about it later that it struck me that Bardem had taken his rib to create Pfeiffer) but when the movie ended it was fairly obvious what it was. Even the grotesque part (Communion and the body of Christ) made sense.

The main problem of people is that they EXPECTED the movie with a real plot, I mean it's logical cause most of the movies are made like that (sadly). Majority of viewers want to have straight plot with bunch of shocking scenes, interesting plot not allegories and metaphors about which they should think afterwards. I understand it but for me it's a sad fact. It is called ART. Okey I expect comments like yes it's shitty art then. But at least for me this movie (art) was like a moving picture movie, where all scenes were dived into the blocks. It was like a picture  from the famous painter which you can ADMIRE or HATE it. I admire it how it was done and hate what it expresses. And that's why I love this movie overall. It's not that "funky-bloddy" horror movie, I wouldn't categorize this movie either. It was something innovative just like Cloud Atlas. I can start talking about its all details (impossible) but at least I want to hightlight two things. 

SPOILERS. The destruction of the house also expressed how the things in our real world are, how we treat our mother of nature. Overpopulation, people were coming and coming, hunger, problems of different cultures, religions or just people who have different opinions, then suddenly the military came and wanted to make a peace or what which makes even more chaos, some people were painted the house, they wanted to fix the house (nature) or protected her literally (the soldier) but it was too late. Secondly I find her husband not only as symbol of god but also as life itself which demands to survive even in ashes and needs mother of nature for it. Her heart is pure good and wisdom to how all things must be kept  in balance and harmony. All in all selfishness of life and people  bring  the world to the ultimate end. How many cycles do we have to wait till it changes??

Title: mother! movie (2017) - official trailer - paramount pictures
Comment:
I can't say that I've quite been able to put my finger on what Mother! means (or if it even has a meaning),
but I absolutely loved it. This is exactly the sort of risky, "out there" cinema I've been missing for far too long.
So of course it flopped and people hate it! I suppose it doesn't lend itself very well to memes and hashtags...

I didn't find it to be horrific, though, which perhaps was Aronofsky's intention. It's classified as a psychological horror film.
Instead, I thought that it was SO over the top that eventually the absurdity of it all turned darkly comedic.
Which is fortunate, because I'd rather watch something outrageous than some kind of symbolic take on motherhood
and its inherent protective and nurturing qualities against nature and the world. Or love.

I have a sneaking suspicion that the film was intended as just such a symbolic device for Aronofsky's philosophical
ideas, but nevertheless, that's not what I got from the film. I got what I wanted to get from it, and it was very entertaining.

It's like a romantic tragedy as envisioned by Terry Gilliam. And that can only be a good thing.

Title: mother! movie (2017) - official trailer - paramount pictures
Comment:
A total mindfuck indeed but not in a good way.
Javier Bardem was amazing in No County For Old Men and although he was great in this as well, the best part of the movie was seeing JL in a see through top at the very beginning...
I watched the entire movie waiting for the big 'reveal' which never ended up happening.
For those that claim you have to be 'smart' to understand it, there is nothing to understand. It was a good attempt but failed miserably and I found myself increasingly frustrated that it wasn't going anywhere. It builds up to a dramatic peak and then stops several times, then you start climbing again but you do so with less enthusiasm each time and for good reason because the movie finally builds up into one crazy flowing scene but then ends only to start right back at the beginning.
Great actors and great acting throughout but speaking on behalf of someone who has half a brain it missed the mark and it slots into the '2 hours I will never get back' category.

I was laughing through the whole film, and trust me i'm a guy who loves this director and all of his previous films, but i'm really sad of how simple minded he thought of his own audiences, i got exactly what he was trying to say, but to me it was just such a simplistic way of story telling. watch the film as if Jennifer lawrence and javier bardem was not in it, watch it as if a normal ordinary guy was the director and the writer of it i'm sure you would have hold a different opinion but if not, you are entitled to your feelings and your own opinions.

*Movie Explanation*  (SPOILER) It's called mother because Jen represents Mother Earth. The husband is like god and you know how he invited the people over? God created humans. Mother Earth worked hard to create earth. Jen/mother worked hard to build the house. The house is earth. Human overpopulation, humans not caring about the earth and remember the part when the couple were painting the house? It's how humans are making the earth how they want it but not how it's supposed to be. Like building buildings and factories. The house is destroyed. How humans are destroying the earth. That's also why the husband didn't die. Because he's god. Reincarnation is how the other woman was there at the end. And remember how in the beginning, the older woman (not mother) said "why don't you buy a new house instead of building this one after it was burnt down?" Him is the God, the creator! Mother is the mother earth. Mother gives form and maintains the structure. God first invites Adam (the old man). Then from Adam's rib God creates Eve. Do you remember the scene in which Man's rib was wounded and he was throwing up?

Adam and Eve break the forbidden crystal (they ate the forbidden fruit).

Then we see the story of Abel and Cane. Cane kills Abel. Then mother's house, the earth, is populated with various religions and various ideologies. All of which pray God (or Him). But they become aggressive. They start to betray the earth. 

And then the story of Jesus. Mother becomes Mary. It gives birth to Jesus. But Jesus followers eat him alive. They eat his blood and his flesh (wine and bread). And the story continues. The way the humanity is heading, Mother earth is doomed.

I liked the symbolism in this movie. But to me, as a semi-Nietzschean thinker, mother is the real God. For God is not separated from mother. God is mother's creation. 

Mother = Earth.

Title: mother! movie (2017) - official trailer - paramount pictures
Comment:
***SPOILERS ALERT ***
*** This review may contain spoilers ***

First of all, please don't watch this film if you have trouble understanding metaphors & symbolism.

It's pretty clear that there are quite a number of reviews/rants on this page with people expressing their hate towards the story and how it's been portrayed on screen. It's strange because it looks like they had absolutely no idea what they were watching... it's trivial and shallow to publish a review without any research. However, I do agree that it isn't an easy one to sit through, but some of the greatest films aren't. So again, please don't bother checking it out if your mind is closed, you won't appreciate this masterpiece.

To help deter unaccommodating opinions being regurgitated, I'll try to explain what made the film worth your time.

I believe there are two themes that can be interpreted from Mother!! Therefore, the use of an additional explanation mark is required.

Religious Theory;

Pretty sure the inconvenient truth to this theory is that when the sh*t hits the fan, mother doesn't like people messing up her house (Earth). Apparently, Darren Aronofsky is not religious but he likes strong environmental messages. He also wrote the script in 5 days.. how long did it take God to create the world? Just saying.

Jennifer Lawrence is (Mother) Earth â€” The house is Earth.

Javier Bardem (Him) is God â€” Creator of life on Earth, loves attention, and forgives everyone.

Ed Harris (Man) is Adam â€” Invited by God to Earth (aka house)

Michelle Pfeiffer (Woman) is Eve â€” Created from Adam's rib (scene where Ed Harris was sick on the toilet)

The crystal is the forbidden fruit (apple)

The baby is the bread at the last supper "Body of Christ"

Relationship Theory;

An extreme version of anxiety in a relationship that is deteriorating. The tense build-up in social interactions and how someone may view a scenario where they feel left out and forgotten. The jealousy someone feels when their bond is shared. Not paying attention to the needs of one another in a relationship. Having a baby to keep the relationship alive. All these emotions are magnified/multiplied by 100 to the point it's literally terrifying, so crazy that it may make you laugh. Finally, once the love has completely diminished, the only thing left is to leave and start again new.

Either way, this film is unique and original in the way it's portrayed, packaged and presented. 

Hope you can appreciate the beauty of this Gothic religious tale / art-house opera and award the actors & production team that helped make it possible.
Original posted by wasabiteabag http://www.imdb.com/user/ur23932157/

I know the trailer looks GOOD but boy will you be duped. Btw, as an African American, I definitely found this movie not culturally relatable.[For those that saw the movie you'll understand] Ain't no way in hell would ANYBODY that I know would allow that in their house. I found it agitating, unrealistic, and frustrating to watch the entire time. You'll feel emotionally and mentally drained seeing this movie, especially if you're a strong will person. This is the longest review I've ever written. That says a lot.

Title: mother! movie (2017) - official trailer - paramount pictures
Comment: Many people who did not like this movie don't seem to realize this is an allegory. They are only focused on the narcissistic man who drains his partners of all their love and spits them out for the next, younger model. "You don't love me. You just love that I love you," says mother. With the millions of dogs we discard each year in America, this behavior of eating up another being's effection without giving it back should be familiar to many. But the true story here is life on earth, represented as the house before, during, and after mankind's presence. Mother nature's husband is the creator, God. The Genesis story of man plays out from mother nature's perspective. In this house you will see Eden, the Apple, Adam, Eve, Cain and Able, the great flood, and other biblical events that are all symbols of human strife, human nature, and our values that tend to miss the forest for the trees at times. It is a warning of where we are going if we don't stop and pay attention to this house that provides us everything. This is what happens if we don't give love back.

Comment: Aronofsky is known for weird movies n=but this time he took a turn into the road that was taken by the Neon Demon. Disturbing film, all the social chaos and controversial things you can imagine tossed into the life of a Lawrence as she and the house she repaired are trashed and invaded at the invitation of her seemingly immortal (maybe) husband. Really weird film, there are two separated ways to see the film, one can see it from the point of view of the disturbed wife, or from the general social impact on their lives. Plus in the last half hour a surreal imploding of their lives into anarchy seems almost made believed. The scenes of her baby and what happens later are a little tough to watch, religious like baby sacrifice and cannibalism are a bit too much for me. There is a biblical element along the film, that is hard to miss for sure. the beginning of the film is the end, a classic technique that seems well over used, In this one I think it should not have been used for surprising the audience with the sacrifice of the female  to renew the house revealed at the end. Mot his best work, but  DISTURBING, WELL DONE  ONE FOR SURE.

Title: mother! movie (2017) - official trailer - paramount pictures
Comment:
Ok so this interpretation sums up the movie pretty well. If you watched the movie and thought it made no sense you should read it before bashing it. Spoilers ahead:

This was my take on the movie. The whole movie is an analogy of the bible and humanities perspective of God. The house represents paradise/the garden of Eden, with the husband representing god. The husband invites a man and a women into their home who represent Adam and Eve. The prized jewel represents the forbidden fruit. When the couple mess up and break the jewel this reflects Adam and Eve eating the fruit followed by the husband/God ordering them to leave. The couples sons who represent Cain and Abel arrive and kill each other. The blood stain on the floor that won't clean represents sin/mark of Cain. The other guests represent humanity and mankind. When they come into their homemade house/world/perfect creation they cause chaos, anarchy and destruction. Jennifer Lawrence questions why her husband won't get rid of their guests/humanity because of how destructive they are but he won't. This represents God's love for humanity and the hope that he can restore relationship between them. The baby obviously represents Jesus which initially causes peace followed by his murder by the husbands fans/so called followers. With Jenifer Lawrence dying breath she gives her husband/God her love which mends this broken relationship with the fall of man/mental fans. The writers block represents the years of silence of God between the old and new testament. At the end of the movie we see a new actress wake in the bed representing a new heaven and earth with followers of God receiving a new body. If you don't know the bible this would've been hard to follow. I thought it was awesome though.

Comment:
Weird film but I think I sorta understand what the director is trying to say. Either it's about God indulging humanity whilst completely ignoring nature, i.e., climate change. Or it's about the ignorance of humanity refusing to respect nature as it tears itself & the world to pieces because of religion. I'm not quite sure which. Or maybe both? Religion indulges humanity to do what it wants without thinking of the consequences as it refuses to respect nature.

It makes one think & that's always the sign of good work. Of course, the Religious Right in America will burn inside with rage as they believe it to be an attack against their beliefs/values. For me, I think it's a cool religious & political critique of the current era. Basically, the world is going to shit because more time is spent worrying/arguing/acting upon the ''security'' religious faith/conviction provides to a large number of people which blocks progress in tackling real, global problems such as climate change.

Comment: "seeing is believing" the house has an oculus. Oculus in Latin means "eye." Eye may refer to the all seeing eye which fundamentally references Lucifer. She was present, but never really pushed herself. It wasnâ€™t appropriate for me to push that, even though I wasnâ€™t sure how she was going to do it. And I really didnâ€™t get to know the character until we started shooting, and she showed up.â€
Perhaps too much so, at times. â€œI think she hyperventilated and also kind of threw a rib out,â€ he recalls. â€œDuring the big climax of the movie, I mean, she started â€¦â€ He trails off, then gets an emphatic look on his face. â€œShe really went there. The producers were freaking out. We had to sort of calm it down and then go for it again. And the thing is, thereâ€™s so much ability there that somehow she can summon it again and again.â€
And she has to: The film is almost entirely composed of her or her immediate surroundings. â€œThe film is basically either over her shoulder, on her face, or her POV,â€ Aronofsky says. â€œThatâ€™s the only shots. There are a few wide shots when sheâ€™s alone. But beyond that, the camera is basically in three places.â€ The result is an unsettlingly intimate finished product that puts the viewer inside her skin for two increasingly white-knuckled hours.




JEN WAS SAYING:::::
â€œI had to go to a darker place than Iâ€™ve ever been in my life,â€ the actress told Vogue. â€œI didnâ€™t know if Iâ€™d be able to come out ok.â€
During one scene, Lawrence came out with a dislocated rib after she was hyperventilating too intensely, which more or less sounds like standard procedure on an Aronofsky movie. Production had to stop for a short while so the actress could be put on oxygen.
â€œI have oxygen tubes in my nostrils, and Darrenâ€™s like, â€˜It was out of focus; weâ€™ve got to do it again,'â€ Lawrence said. â€œAnd I was just like, â€˜Go fuck yourself.'â€
In order to help Lawrence cope with the incredibly tense material, the crew set up a â€œhappy placeâ€ so that she could escape the set when needed and distance herself from the ordeals of her character. Lawrenceâ€™s â€œhappy placeâ€ consisted of gumballs and a television playing clips on loop of the Kardashians. It may sound ridiculous, but it was needed to make sure Lawrence was always focused for the next take.




â€œItâ€™s such a raw, natural talent she has,â€ Aronofsky said about his leading lady (who also just happens to be his girlfriend of over a year now). â€œI always kind of compare her to Michael Jordan.â€




â€œSheâ€™s a very brave actress with no boundaries and doesnâ€™t need to be hurt in order to create pain,â€ added Bardem about his co-star. â€œSheâ€™s truly committed to go as far as needed.â€




Apparently Lawrence was afraid to go as far as dislocating her rib for the role. The last time a female lead in an Aronofsky movie lost her mind, it was Natalie Portman in â€œBlack Swan.â€ Could â€œmother!â€ bring Lawrence back to the Dolby Theater next year? Jlaw's character is looking at her husband like "who tf are these people don't you see what's wrong with this" meanwhile the audience is like "Jlaw this whole situation is bad don'y you see what's wrong with this". I like the irony of a character that tries to uncover something in a situation that *they* find unsettling, while being blind to a situation that the audience finds unsettling.

Personally in this regard I think the casting is fitting.
